  <p>National security doesn’t get second chances. And there’s a difference between talking about innovation and actually delivering it.</p>
  <p>Government contracts aren’t immune to AI hype circles. Most defense teams face the same wall: slow-moving, locked-in systems built by vendors who sell mystery, not control. The promise of AI gets buried under red tape, “planned” integrations, and sky-high service contracts that move slower than the threats you need to prevent.</p>
  <p>What’s at stake isn’t just data. It’s trust.</p>
  <p>How do you move fast in a world built to slow you down? You break the model. And you do it together.</p>
  <p>That’s where your partnership with Quansight and OpenTeams comes in.</p>

  <h2>The Real Risk Isn’t Open Source. It’s the Lock-In You Already Have.</h2>
  <p>Big tech vendors would have you believe that open source is unpredictable. Untrustworthy. A liability.</p>
  <p>The truth is that 90% of the world’s software is open source. Even proprietary software is just a layer.</p>
  <p>You cannot afford to stay locked into a system. Proprietary software is the real risk.</p>
  <p>It chains you to someone else’s roadmap. It buries you under costs. It blocks your teams from moving fast and forces you to work in the dark—unable to see, change, or control what’s happening behind the curtain.</p>
  <p>The idea that open source is “risky” is a marketing spin.</p>
  <p>Open source is the backbone of modern software, including most commercial platforms. You’re already using it. The difference is now you can own it.</p>

